TY  - JOUR
T1  - Organizational Development: Description, Issues, and Some Research Results
AU  - Kegan, Daniel L.
Y1  - 1971/12/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255060
DO  - 10.5465/255060
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 453
EP  - 464
VL  - 14
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Organizational development (OD) may be defined as an educational strategy employing experienced-based behavior in order to achieve a self-renewing organization. The growth of OD from sensitivity training is discussed, and various issues in current OD practice are raised?including spontaneous and planned approaches to organizational change. Some results of a research project are reported, that supported the hypothesis that: a ?proper? OD program will increase individuals' feelings of trust toward their own work group and toward others, while keeping the individuals aware of the demands of their tasks. However, supplementary research information indicated that OD's norms of confrontation, choice, and collaboration may conflict with traditional bureaucratic values, such as conformity and obedience. Participants in an OD program should be aware that other members of their organization may be hostile to the OD program, and the strategy of the program should reflect an awareness of the organizational climate.
AB  - Organizational development (OD) may be defined as an educational strategy employing experienced-based behavior in order to achieve a self-renewing organization. The growth of OD from sensitivity training is discussed, and various issues in current OD practice are raised?including spontaneous and planned approaches to organizational change. Some results of a research project are reported, that supported the hypothesis that: a ?proper? OD program will increase individuals' feelings of trust toward their own work group and toward others, while keeping the individuals aware of the demands of their tasks. However, supplementary research information indicated that OD's norms of confrontation, choice, and collaboration may conflict with traditional bureaucratic values, such as conformity and obedience. Participants in an OD program should be aware that other members of their organization may be hostile to the OD program, and the strategy of the program should reflect an awareness of the organizational climate.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255060
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255060
Y2  - 2026/04/24
